# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alan-howard-engineer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alan-howard-engineer/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:alan-howard-engineer/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:alan-howard-engineer/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] Budiansky was born in New York City on March 8, 1925, to Russian immigrant parents, Louis and Rose (Chaplick) Budiansky.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] Upon obtaining a Bachelor of Civil Engineering degree from City College of New York in 1944 when he was barely over 19, he became an aeronautical research scientist at the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA, forerunner to NASA) at Langley Field, Virginia.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] He took an educational leave from NACA to enroll in 1947 in the graduate program in applied mathematics at Brown University, completing his Ph.D. in 1950 with a dissertation entitled *Fundamental Theorems and Consequences of the Slip Theory of Plasticity*.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] He returned to Langley in 1950 and, in 1952, was appointed Head of the Structural Mechanics Branch.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] He joined the faculty of Harvard in 1955.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] He made widely cited contributions on the way that fissures and joints in rocks affect the propagation of seismic waves, which has become a standard basis for inferring rock properties in the Earth, and contributed to understanding stressing and deformation in the inflation of the human lung.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] His work of the later years was focused on problems in the domain of materials science, explaining mechanical properties of solids in terms of microscopic mechanisms.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] He referred to this important area as "micromechanics".
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] He was one of its pioneers, and contributed to explanation of the fracture of ductile metals and the toughening of normally brittle ceramics and composite materials.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] Budiansky won many honors including the AIAA 1970 Dryden Research Lecturer; CCNY 1974 Townsend Harris Medal; ASCE 1982 von Karman Medal; Society of Engineering Science 1985 Eringen Medal; ASME 1989 Timoshenko Medal.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] He received honorary doctorates from Northwestern University 1986 and Technion Israel Institute of Technology.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] In addition he was a member of the National Academy of Sciences, the National Academy of Engineering, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences; the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences; and the Danish Center for Applied Mathematics and Mechanics.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] Professional affiliations included: ASCE, ASME, AIAA, and AGU.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] Bernard Budiansky died January 23, 1999, at his home in Lexington, Massachusetts, aged 73.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bernard-budiansky] He was survived by his wife and two sons, one of whom is writer Stephen Budiansky.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He was also the co-principal investigator (co-PI) and program manager on Gravity Probe B, which tested gravitomagnetism and was the first direct mechanical test of Einstein’s General Relativity.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He has received numerous awards and honors for GPS and contributions to engineering and invention, including the Charles Stark Draper Prize, National Inventors Hall of Fame, and IEEE Medal of Honor, among others.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 2019, Bradford Parkinson shared the Queen Elizabeth Prize for Engineering with three other GPS pioneers (James Spilker, Hugo Freuhauf, and Richard Schwartz).
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] For his secondary education, Parkinson attended the Breck School, then a small, all-boys preparatory school, graduating in 1952.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson has credited his experiences at the Breck School for inspiring in him an early love of math and science, an interest which eventually became his life's calling.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson was a distinguished graduate of the United States Naval Academy, graduating in 1957 with a Bachelor of Science in Engineering.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] While studying there, Parkinson discovered he had a deep interest in controls engineering, which was introduced in a Senior Level course at the time.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Fortunately, one of Parkinson's Electrical Engineering professors was an Air Force officer who urged him to consider being commissioned in the Air Force rather than the Navy.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson also knew he wanted to get a Ph.D. later in life, and the Air Force was more receptive to graduate and post-graduate education at this time.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] After being commissioned in the Air Force, he was trained in electronics maintenance and supervised large ground radar installations in Washington state.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He then was sponsored by USAF to attend MIT, studying controls engineering, inertial guidance, astronautics and electrical engineering.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson worked in the lab of Charles Stark Draper, the namesake for the prestigious Draper Prize which Parkinson went on to win later in his life.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] At MIT, he received a Master of Science in Aeronautics and Astronautics in 1961 and was elected to the Tau Beta Pi and Sigma Xi honor Societies.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson was then assigned to work at the Central Inertial Guidance Test Facility at Holloman Air Force Base in Alamogordo, New Mexico.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] There he developed tests and was a Chief Analyst for the evaluation of the Air Force’s inertial guidance systems and continued work on electrical and controls engineering.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 1964, after three years at Holloman, Parkinson was assigned to a Ph.D. program at Stanford University graduating in 1966, with a degree in Aeronautics and Astronautics.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] After graduating from the Naval Academy, Parkinson opted to perform regular Air Force duty in order to, as he put it, “find out what the Air Force was all about”.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He served two years as Chief Communications-Electronics officer at an early warning station In Washington State.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] After finishing his Ph.D. at Stanford, he was assigned to the U.S.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Air Force Test Pilot School (1966–68) as an academic instructor and was chief of their Simulation Division.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He also was chief academic instructor to a class of USAF Astronauts, including many who later joined NASA and flew on the Space Shuttle.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He then attended the Air Force Command and Staff College for a year where he became a Distinguished Graduate.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Next, he was assigned as a Professor and Deputy Head of the Air Force Academy Department of Astronautics and Computer Science.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In the midst of his first year he was detached to help with the development of a brand-new version of the AC-130 gunship.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In particular, he led the final development of the innovative digital fire-control system.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] After successful testing at Eglin Air Force Base, he deployed to South East Asia during the Vietnam War and flew 26 combat missions to continue evaluation and refinement of the weapons system.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] During this deployment he logged more than 170 hours of combat missions, and was awarded a number of military honors including the Bronze Star, Meritorious Service Medal, two Air Medals and a Presidential Unit Citation.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He then returned to the Air Force Academy as the Head of the Department of Astronautics and Computer Science.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He next was a student at the Naval War College, in Newport, Rhode Island, for a year where he graduated with distinction and was followed by a brief assignment as the Chief Engineer of the Advanced Ballistic Re-Entry System (ABRES) project, at Los Angeles Air Force Station.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 1973, thanks in part to the influence of his mentor, General William W.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Dunn, the Commander, Lt-Gen Kenneth Schultz, assigned Parkinson to a floundering Air Force program called Project 621B.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] This program had been trying to gain approval for a new satellite-based navigation system concept.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Strong technical support was rendered by The Aerospace Corporation.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson quickly recruited a small cadre of highly competent Air Force Officer-Engineers, with Masters and PhDs from top universities.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He then assumed lead responsibility to sell the new configuration to the Air Force and to top Pentagon Officials.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] By December 1973 he gained approval and budget for a four satellite, live demonstration of the new idea.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] This included the concept of flying Atomic clocks in high orbits that had been advocated by both the Naval Research Laboratory and an earlier USAF Aerospace study by J.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson then assumed full, direct control of the development of the demonstration system, which included satellites, a global ground control system, nine types of user receivers, and an extensive land, sea and air test program.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He testified before congress and explained that there would be an “at-risk” signal to freely support civilian applications of precision positioning from the outset.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 1978, Parkinson was the launch Commander for the first prototype GPS satellite to be launched (forty-four months after go-ahead).
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Later that year, the test program verified every performance claim that Parkinson had made.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson was then offered a job as the Air Force aid to the Secretary of Defense.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson rather elected to retire from the Air Force.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Over the course of his 26-year military career, Parkinson served twenty-one years in the Air Force, from 1957 to 1978, and five years with the Navy.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] After retiring from the Air Force in 1978, Parkinson spent one year as a professor of Mechanical Engineering at Colorado State University, Fort Collins.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Soon after, he accepted a position as Vice President at the Space Systems Group of the Rockwell International (later absorbed into Boeing), where he was involved in strategic planning and developing advanced—and classified—space systems.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] From 1980 to 1984, he was vice president and general manager of the Boston software company Intermetrics, which was responsible for creating the currently used HAL/S programming language for NASA’s Space Shuttle program.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He was heavily involved in the company’s initial public offering in 1982.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 1984, he left Intermetrics to accept an appointment as a Research Professor at Stanford University.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Shortly after, he became a tenured Professor and assumed Stanford’s “Edward C.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Wells” Chair of Aeronautics and Astronautics.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 1999, he took a leave of absence for a year and served as the CEO of the Sunnyvale based company, Trimble Navigation, a producer of advanced positioning systems.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He then returned to his faculty position at Stanford.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 2001 he briefly retired from Stanford and named Emeritus, but was immediately recalled and is currently active, albeit at a lower activity level.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He was also the co-principal investigator and program manager on the NASA/Stanford University endeavor Gravity Probe B, which tested gravitomagnetism and was the first ever direct mechanical test of Einstein’s General Relativity.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Using orbiting gyroscopes in satellites, they measured the geodetic effect and frame-dragging.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Under NASA sponsorship, this was successfully launched from Vandenberg Air Force Base on April 20, 2004.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] While the spaceflight phase completed in 2005, the results were announced and published from 2007 to as late as 2015.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] A Stanford-based analysis group and NASA announced on 4 May 2011 that the data from GP-B indeed confirms the two predictions of Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He has been on many corporate and governmental boards and recently stepped down as Chairman of Jet Propulsion Laboratory’s Advisory Council after thirteen years in the position, long past the usual two-year tenure.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He still serves as Co-Chair for the National Executive Committee for Space-Based PNT Advisory Board.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Beginning with the landmark launch of Sputnik in 1957, the first man-made satellite, members of the aeronautical and military spheres realized that satellite-based positioning was technically feasible, perhaps likely.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] The United States Navy experimented with the technology in 1960, launching the Transit positioning satellites which was mainly used for submarine navigation, in particular for initializing their on-board ballistic missiles.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] However, Transit only provided two-dimensional, periodic fixes every several hours with an accuracy of about one-tenth to one-quarter mile.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Additional, satellite-based, navigation systems were proposed or launched throughout the 1960s including by the USAF/Aerospace Corporation, the Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory, and the Naval Research Laboratory.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] But because of the secrecy and competition for budgets, of such military endeavors, collaboration was minimal.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Also, their collective promise of accuracy was not credible to Pentagon officials and they publicly voiced their skepticism of the whole premise.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] They did not believe the usefulness would justify the cost.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson was met with extreme resistance, but used small-scale prototypes sell what would go on to become GPS.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] With the advent of The Information Age and the accompanying mobile technology, GPS has become a ubiquitous and life-changing technology to all sectors, critical even.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] For example, current cell phones include GPS receivers, and when used in conjunction with GIS like Google Maps, accurate and real-time directions can be used by pedestrian and civilian traffic alike.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Indeed, with GPS, airplanes are now capable of landing on autopilot, and doing so with better precision and safety than human pilots.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Outside of military and standard civilian use, seismologists are testing GPS for use in earthquake detection and measurement.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] The timing systems—atomic clocks—made popular by GPS, are vital to the functionality of incalculable amounts of Internet services, including the banking and stock markets.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 1983, President Reagan stated that GPS would be guaranteed to the world, in response to the Soviet downing of a Korean Airliner.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] A recent study for the US government estimated the yearly benefit of GPS to be 37 to 74 billion dollars, excluding many of the applications, such as saving lives, that were difficult to quantify.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson has received numerous awards and honors from private organizations, the military, and government bodies, largely for his work on GPS.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Parkinson is an honorary fellow of the Royal institute of Navigation and the AIAA.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Also he is a fellow of the American Astronautical Society, and the American Institute of Navigation and he was elected to the National Academy of Engineering in 1990 and elected to the International Academy of Astronautics.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] NASA awarded him with both the Public Service Medal in 1994 and the Distinguished Public Service Medal in 2001.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 2003 he shared the Draper Prize with Ivan A.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 2004 he was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 2018, he was awarded the IEEE Medal of Honor, their highest award, after previously being awarded their Kershner, Pioneer, M.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] The UK’s Institute of Navigation awarded him in 1983 with their Gold Medal and the counterpart US organization of the same name awarded him with their Thurlow, Burka, and Kepler awards in 1986, 1987, and 1991.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] In 2009, he was the recipient of the Air Force Space Command's Air Force Space and Missile Pioneers.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Consumer Technology inducted him into their Hall of Fame in 2010.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Asteroid 10041 Parkinson, discovered by Carolyn and Eugene Shoemaker at Palomar Observatory in 1985, was named in his honor.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] The official naming citation was published by the Minor Planet Center on 21 September 2002 (M.P.C.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] His military awards, in addition to those mentioned for his combat experience, include the Legion of Merit and the Defense Superior Performance Medal.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He was selected as a “Distinguished Graduate” of the US Naval Academy in 2011, and an “Engineering Hero” of Stanford in 2012.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Bradford Parkinson was born in Madison, Wisconsin on February 16, 1935, but grew up in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] He is the only son of Herbert Parkinson, an architect who was also an alumnus of MIT.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Patent 5,726,659, “Multipath calibration in GPS pseudorange measurements” Parkinson, U.S.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Patent 6,434,462, “GPS control of a tractor-towed implement" Parkinson, U.S.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Patent 6,732,024, “Method and apparatus for vehicle control, navigation and positioning" Parkinson, U.S.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Patent 6,052,647, “Method and system for automatic control of vehicles based on carrier phase differential GPS" Parkinson, U.S.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Patent 6,373,432, "System using leo satellites for centimeter-level navigation" Parkinson, U.S.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/bradford-w-parkinson] Patent 5,572,218, "System and method for generating precise position determinations" Parkinson, U.S.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] Mote was born in San Francisco, California and received his bachelor's degree, masters, and doctorate degrees from the University of California, Berkeley in mechanical engineering.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] After a postdoctoral year in England and three years as an assistant professor at the Carnegie Institute of Technology in Pittsburgh, he returned to Berkeley to join the faculty in mechanical engineering for the next 31 years.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] He and his students investigated the dynamics, stability, and control of high-speed rotating and translating continua (e.g., disks, webs, tapes, and cables) as well as biomechanical problems emanating from snow skiing.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] He coined the area called "dynamics of axially moving materials" encompassing these systems.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] He has authored or co-authored over 300 academic publications, and has mentored 58 Ph.D. students.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] At Berkeley, he held an endowed chair in mechanical systems and served as chair of the mechanical engineering department from 1987 to 1991 when the National Research Council (NRC) ranked its graduate program effectiveness highest nationally.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] Because of his success at raising funds for mechanical engineering, in 1991 he was appointed vice chancellor at Berkeley expressly to create and lead a $1 billion capital campaign for the campus that ultimately reached $1.4 billion.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] Mote was recruited to the presidency of the University of Maryland, College Park, a position he held until 2010 when he was appointed Regents Professor.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] His goal for the university was to elevate its self-expectation of achievement and its national and global position through proactive initiatives.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] During his tenure the number of Academy members among the faculty tripled, three Nobel laureates were recognized, and an accredited school of public health and a new department of bioengineering were created.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] He also founded a 130-acre research park next to the campus, faculty research funds increased by 150%, and partnerships with surrounding federal agencies and with international organizations expanded greatly.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] The Academic Ranking of World Universities ranked the campus #36 in 2010 and its Engineering School #13 globally.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] Mote was elected a member of the National Academy of Engineering in 1988 for analysis of the mechanics of complex dynamic systems, providing results of great practical importance in vibrations and biomechanics.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] He was also elected to the positions of Councillor (2002-2008), Treasurer (2009-2013), and President for six years beginning July 1, 2013.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] He serves as vice chair of the National Research Council (NRC) and has served on its Governing Board Executive Committee since 2009.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] He also served as vice chair of the NRC Committee on the Department of Defense Basic Research (2004) and on the NRC committee authoring the Rising Above the Gathering Storm reports of 2005 and 2010.
[src:alan-howard-engineer/c-daniel-mote-jr] He was also a founding member of the FBI's National Security Higher Education Advisory Board (2005-2010).
